With the following code, it should offer to peak/go-to definition when on the var(), the same as for variables in LESS and SASS files:

``` CSS
:root {
    --bg-color: #ccc;
}

body {
  background-color: var(--bg-color);
}
```

Currently VS Code is not aware of CSS variables.

Documentation states:

”Goto Declaration and Find References
“This is supported for keyframes and variables in the same file.”

but it doesn’t look like this works for @keyframes (it does work for SASS variables)

For example with the following code:

``` css
@keyframes progress {
    0% { background-position: 0; opacity: 0; }
    100% { background-position: 100% 0; opacity: 0; }
}

body {
  animation-name: progress;
}
```

Results in this:

![screen shot 2016-02-17 at 1 50 49 am](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/465069/13105575/b93e3076-d518-11e5-8969-c28188d6a10c.png)

I'd expect it to go to the keyframes line when I right click on animation-name's value.

Strangely if you right click on any of the properties inside the keyframes, it offers both options, but they do nothing (as there is no definition) 

![screen shot 2016-02-17 at 1 52 37 am](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/465069/13105622/f64b57aa-d518-11e5-8fbf-2e45d626d65d.png)

Use the following snippet:

``` typescript
class Bla {
    items : string[];
    item : string;

    constructor() {
        this.item.
    }

    public blarg() {

    }
}
```

Place the cursor after the "this.item." and trigger autocomplete with CTRL+SPACE and notice that no suggestions are displayed. In contrast if you remove the "." and type "." again suggestions are shown.

I'm currently trying to create a basic extension for VSCode. I would like to register a provider with the function `registerOnTypeFormattingEditProvider`.

I found some examples of code on Github to write the provider and make the subscription.

The code of the provider:

```
'use strict';

import { OnTypeFormattingEditProvider, TextDocument, Position, FormattingOptions, CancellationToken, TextEdit } from 'vscode';

export class DartCommentsProvider implements OnTypeFormattingEditProvider {

    public provideOnTypeFormattingEdits(document: TextDocument, position: Position, ch: string, options: FormattingOptions, token: CancellationToken): Thenable<TextEdit[]>{
        console.log("Character typed:", ch);    

        return new Promise((resolve, reject) => {
          return [];
        });
    } 
}
```

The subscription:

```
import * as vscode from 'vscode'; 

import { DartDocumentFormattingEditProvider, Formatter} from './dartFormat';
import { DartCommentsProvider } from './dartComments';
import { DartHoverCustomProvider } from './dartHover';

// this method is called when your extension is activated
// your extension is activated the very first time the command is executed
export function activate(ctx: vscode.ExtensionContext) {

    let dartDocumentFilter: vscode.DocumentFilter = {language : 'dart', scheme:'file'};

    ctx.subscriptions.push(vscode.languages.registerHoverProvider(dartDocumentFilter,new DartHoverCustomProvider()));

    //Registration
    ctx.subscriptions.push(vscode.languages.registerOnTypeFormattingEditProvider(dartDocumentFilter,new DartCommentsProvider(), ';', '/'));   
}

// this method is called when your extension is deactivated
export function deactivate() {
}
```

When I press `;` or  `/`, the function `provideOnTypeFormattingEdits` is not called.
